The motivas for Domitian’s conduct here given must not be accepted without some allowance. Agricola had been governor of Britain for a longer period than any of his pred· ecessors. His campaigns were very expensive and yielded no oom- mensurate results. Domitian had not the interest in Britain that Vespasian and Titus had; finally the Dacian revolt was upon him, so that the emperor may well have been justified in checking Agric- ola's lust of conquest.
